PYTHON

2021-07-18 Sun 03:29 PM
    
    \_ Started reading Automate the boring stuff with python
        \_ What to learn
            \_ Moving and renaming thousands of files and sorting them into folders
            \_ Filling out online forms -- no typing required
            \_ Downloading files or copying text from a website whenever it updates 
            \_ Having your computer text you custom notifications 
            \_ Updating or formatting Excel spreadsheets 
            \_ Checking your email and sending out prewritten responses
        \_ Lists
            \_ example
                \_ test = ['im a string', 2, None, True, 3.1416]
            \_ accessing values
                \_ same like arrays in C
                \_ can use slicing
                    \_ test[1:4]  # returns [2, None, True]
                \_ negative index
                    \_ test[-1]  # returns 3.1416
                \_ range(len(list)) with `for` loop
                \_ enumerate() function   
                    \_ returns two values: index, items on list
            \_ changing values
                \_ test[2] = False  # returns ['im a string', 2, False, True, 3.1416]
            \_ removing values
                \_ del test[2]  # returns ['im a string', 2, True, 3.1416]
            \_ multiple assignment to multiple variables
                \_ should be same number of variables and len(list)
                \_ example
                    \_ info1, info2, info3, info4, info5 = test  # assignment 
                    \_ # result from multi assignment
                        \_ info1 = 'im a string'
                           info2 = 2
                           info3 = None 
                           info4 = True
                           info5 = 3.1416 
            \_ functions
                \_ random.choice()
                \_ random.shuffle()
            \_ methods
                \_ .index(<value>) 
                \_ .append(<value>)
                \_ .insert(<index>, <value>)
                \_ .remove(<value>)  # use when value is known on the list
                                     # use `del` when index is known on the list 
                \_ .sort(None)  # ASCIIbetical order ['A', 'B', 'C', 'a', 'b'] 
                    \_ .sort(reverse=True) 
                    \_ .sort(key=str.lower)  #returns ['a', 'A', 'b', 'B', 'C']
                \_ .reverse(None)  # not sorted; returns as it is but flipped 

        \_ `in` and `not in` operator

















